rrative prose, Hite proposes, thus refrains from endorsing a single position, not only adding value ambiguity to the cognitive ambiguity associated with modernist fiction generally, but explicitly rejecting the polemical intent of feminist novelists in the generation preceding her own. Hite also points out that Woolf reconsidered her rejection of polemical fiction later in her career. In the unfinished draft of her "essay-novel" The Pargiters, Woolf created a brilliant new narrative form allowing her to make unequivocal value judgments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish fictionxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFeminism and literaturezEnglish-speaking countriesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFeminist fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aWomen and literaturezEnglish-speaking countriesxHistoryy20th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aWomens Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501726316zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501726316zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501726316/original  a978-3-11-053617-1 Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA